# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cutting-tool-machining
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] An **abrasive saw**, also known as a **cut-off saw** or **chop saw**, is a circular saw (a kind of power tool) which is typically used to cut hard materials, such as metals, tile, and concrete.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] The cutting action is performed by an abrasive disc, similar to a thin grinding wheel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Technically speaking this is not a saw, as it does not use regularly shaped edges (teeth) for cutting.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] These saws are available in a number of configurations, including table top, free hand, and walk behind models.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] In the table top models, which are commonly used to cut tile and metal, the cutting wheel and motor are mounted on a pivoting arm attached to a fixed base plate.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Table top saws are often electrically powered and generally have a built-in vise or other clamping arrangement.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] The free hand designs are typically used to cut concrete, asphalt, and pipe on construction sites.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] They are designed with the handles and motor near the operator, with the blade at the far end of the saw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Free hand saws do not feature a vise, because the materials being cut are larger and heavier.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Walk-behind models, sometimes called flat saws are larger saws which use a stand or cart to cut into concrete floors as well as asphalt and concrete paving materials.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Abrasive saws typically use composite friction disk blades known as "cutoff wheels/blades" to abrasively cut through the steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] The blades are consumable items as they wear throughout the cut.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] The abrasive blades for these saws are typically 14 in (360 mm) in diameter and 7⁄64 in (2.8 mm) thick, though they can be thousandths of an inch thick and only 2" in diameter.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Larger saws use 410 mm (16 in) diameter blades.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Blades are available for steel and stainless steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Abrasive saws can also use superabrasive (i.e., diamond and cubic boron nitride or CBN) blades, which last longer than conventional abrasive materials and do not generate as hazardous particulate matter.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Superabrasive materials are more commonly used when cutting concrete, asphalt, and tile; however, they are also suitable for cutting ferrous metals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Rubber-bonded abrasives are a niche but important sector of the abrasive cutoff wheel manufacturing space.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] These blades can be extremely thin and use specialized machines known as "Cutoff Machines".
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] These machines use the extremely thin rubber-bonded wheels to reduce loss of material compared to a thicker-metal blade which would produce burring, lose more material, and cause inconsistent finishes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Rubber-bonded blades finish as they cut reducing the time it take to produce sections of materials such as Molybdenum, Inconel, Steel, Iron, Brass, and more.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Many industries such as the aerospace industry and automotive industry use these wheels to produce fasteners and bolts with extremely precise measurements.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Since their introduction, portable cut-off saws have made many building site jobs easier.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] With these saws, lightweight steel fabrication previously performed in workshops using stationary power bandsaws or cold saws can be done on-site.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] Abrasive saws have replaced more expensive and hazardous acetylene torches in many applications, such as cutting rebar.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-saw] In addition, these saws allow construction workers to cut through concrete, asphalt, and pipe on job sites in a more precise manner than is possible with heavy equipment.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] A **diamond tool** is a cutting tool with diamond grains fixed on the functional parts of the tool via a bonding material or another method.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] As diamond is a superhard material, diamond tools have many advantages as compared with tools made with common abrasives such as corundum and silicon carbide.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] In *Natural History*, Pliny wrote "When an *adamas* is successfully broken it disintegrates into splinters so small as to be scarcely visible.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Diamond is one of the hardest natural materials on earth; much harder than corundum and silicon carbide.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Diamond also has high strength, good wear resistance, and a low friction coefficient.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] So when used as an abrasive, it has many obvious advantages over many other common abrasives.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] There are thousands of kinds of diamond tools.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] They can be categorized by their manufacturing methods and their uses.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] If categorized by use, there are diamond grinding tools, diamond cutting tools (e.g., diamond coated twist drill bits), diamond drilling tools, diamond sawing tools (e.g., diamond saw blades), diamond drawing dies, etc.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The tools made with common abrasives (e.g. corundum and silicon carbide) can also do the task.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Besides what are listed above, there are also other domains where diamond tools are applied, for example, in medicine, Venezuelan scientist Humberto Fernandez Moran invented the diamond knife for use in delicate surgeries in 1955.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Apart from its use as an abrasive due to its high hardness, diamond is also used to make other products for its many other good properties such as high heat-conductivity, low friction coefficient, high chemical stability, high resistivity and high optical performances.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] These applications include coatings on bearings and CDs, acting as lens and thermistors, making high-voltage switches and sensors, etc.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Multipoint tools have higher accuracy, especially in form grinding, where blade types are used.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The thickness is controlled and blades are available in thicknesses from 0.75 to 1.40 millimeters (0.030 to 0.055 in).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Grit-type tools are of a tough grade, and can be used for bench grinders.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Since small points are used, the diamonds have a cutting edge with natural points, unlike single-point tools, which have brutted points.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The cost of multipoint tools is lower, since smaller, less expensive diamonds are used.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Most wafers are polished to a mirror finish, then cut with an electrical discharge machining (EDM) tool into smaller, workable segments that are then brazed onto the sawblade, reamer, drill, or other tool.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Often they are EDM machined and/or ground an additional time to expose the vein of diamond along the cutting edge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] These tools are mostly used for the machining of nonmetallic and nonferrous materials.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The grinding operation is combined with EDM for several reasons.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] For example, according to Modern Machine Shop, the combination allows a higher material removal rate and is therefore more cost effective.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Also, the EDM process slightly affects the surface finish.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Grinding is used on the affected area to provide a finer final surface.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The Beijing Institute of Electro-Machining attributes a finer shaping and surface geometry to the combination of the two processes into one.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The process itself is accomplished by combining the two elements from each individual process into one grinding wheel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The diamond graphite wheel accomplishes the task of grinding, while the graphite ring around the existing wheel serves as the EDM portion.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] However, since diamond is not a conductive material, the bonding in the PCD work piece must be ample enough to provide the conductivity necessary for the EDG process to work.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Polycrystalline diamond tools are used extensively in automotive and aerospace industries.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] They are ideal for speed machining (9000 surface feet per minute or higher) in tough and abrasive aluminum alloys, and high-abrasion processes such as carbon-fiber drilling and ceramics.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The diamond cutting edges make them last for extended periods before replacement is needed.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] High volume processes, tight tolerances, and highly abrasive processes are ideal for diamond tooling.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] In the late 1970s, General Electric pioneered the technology of **polycrystalline diamond compacts** (PDCs) as a replacement for natural diamonds in drill bits.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] PDCs have been used to cut through crystalline rock surfaces for extended periods of time in lab environments, and these capabilities have now been implemented in harsh environments throughout the world.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Department of Energy claimed that nearly one-third of the total footage drilled worldwide is being drilled with PDC bits, with a claimed savings of nearly $100,000 per PDC bit as compared to roller-core bits.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Diamond pastes are used for polishing materials that require a mirror finish.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] They are often used in metallurgical specimens, carbide dies, carbide seals, spectacle glass industry, and for polishing diamonds.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Diamond paste is mainly used in industrial requirements for polishing and sharpening metal blades and other metal surfaces.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The paste is not just to polish the metal blade but sharpen the cutting edge as well.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Diamond powder deposited through electroplating is used to make files (including nail files) and in small grinding applications.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Single point diamond turning (SPDT) utilizes a solid, flawless diamond as the cutting edge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The single crystalline diamond can be natural or synthetic, and is sharpened to the desired dimensions by mechanical grinding and polishing.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The cutting edge of most diamond tools is sharp to tens of nanometers, making it very effective for cutting non-ferrous materials with high resolution.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] SPDT is a very accurate machining process, used to create finished aspherical and irregular optics without the need for further polishing after completion.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] The most accurate machine tool in the world, the LODTM, formerly at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, had a profile accuracy estimated at 28 nm, while most machines seek a roughness within that deviation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] SPDT is used for optics, for flat surfaces where both surface finish and unusually high dimensional accuracy are required, and when lapping would be uneconomical or impractical.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] For high-speed gas powered cut-off saws, walk-behind saws, handheld grinders, bridge saws, table saws, tile saws, and other types of saws.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] For cutting curves in countertops to install sinks or sculpt statues.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Thick diamond blades for restoration, involving grinding and replacing mortar.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Thick V-shaped diamond blades for repairing cracks in concrete.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Typically used on hand grinders for grinding concrete or stone.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Hollow steel tube with diamond tipped segments for drilling holes through concrete walls in the construction industry, porcelain tiles or granite worktops in the domestic industry, or also used for sample core extractions in the mining industry.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Used in machine tools for machining ceramics and high speed aluminium.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Used in turning centers for optics and precision surfaces.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] Pads with diamond crystals for polishing marble and other fine stone.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive-tool] For cutting stone, concrete and brick with a special chainsaw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] An **alloy** is a mixture of chemical elements of which in most cases at least one is a metallic element, although it is also sometimes used for mixtures of elements; herein only **metallic alloys** are described.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Metallic alloys often have properties that differ from those of the pure elements from which they are made.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The vast majority of metals used for commercial purposes are alloyed to improve their properties or behavior, such as increased strength, hardness or corrosion resistance.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Metals may also be alloyed to reduce their overall cost, for instance alloys of gold and copper.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In an alloy, the atoms are joined by metallic bonding rather than by covalent bonds typically found in chemical compounds.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The alloy constituents are usually measured by mass percentage for practical applications, and in atomic fraction for basic science studies.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Alloys are usually classified as substitutional or interstitial alloys, depending on the atomic arrangement that forms the alloy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] They can be further classified as homogeneous (consisting of a single phase), or heterogeneous (consisting of two or more phases) or intermetallic.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] An alloy may be a solid solution of metal elements (a single phase, where all metallic grains (crystals) are of the same composition) or a mixture of metallic phases (two or more solutions, forming a microstructure of different crystals within the metal).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Examples of alloys include red gold (gold and copper), white gold (gold and silver), sterling silver (silver and copper), steel or silicon steel (iron with non-metallic carbon or silicon respectively), solder, brass, pewter, duralumin, bronze, and amalgams.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Alloys are used in a wide variety of applications, from the steel alloys used in everything from buildings to automobiles to surgical tools, to exotic titanium alloys used in the aerospace industry, to beryllium-copper alloys for non-sparking tools.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] An alloy is a mixture of chemical elements which forms an impure substance (admixture) that retains the characteristics of a metal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Alloys are made by mixing two or more elements, at least one of which is a metal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This is usually called the primary metal or the base metal, and the name of this metal may also be the name of the alloy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The other constituents may or may not be metals but, when mixed with the molten base, they will be soluble and dissolve into the mixture.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The mechanical properties of alloys will often be quite different from those of its individual constituents.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] A metal that is normally very soft (malleable), such as aluminium, can be altered by alloying it with another soft metal, such as copper.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Although both metals are very soft and ductile, the resulting aluminium–copper alloy will have much greater strength.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Adding a small amount of non-metallic carbon to iron trades its great ductility for the greater strength of an alloy called steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Due to its very-high strength, but still substantial toughness, and its ability to be greatly altered by heat treatment, steel is one of the most useful and common alloys in modern use.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] By adding chromium to steel, its resistance to corrosion can be enhanced, creating stainless steel, while adding silicon will alter its electrical characteristics, producing silicon steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Like oil and water, a molten metal may not always be miscible with another element.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For example, lithium, magnesium, or silver are almost completely insoluble with pure iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Even when the constituents are soluble, each will usually have a saturation point, beyond which no more of the constituent can be added.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Iron, for example, can stably hold a maximum of 6.67% carbon, forming a compound called cementite.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Although the elements of an alloy usually must be soluble in the liquid state, they may not always be soluble in the solid state.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] If the metals remain soluble when solid, the alloy forms a solid solution, becoming a homogeneous structure consisting of identical crystals, called a phase.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] If as the mixture cools the constituents become insoluble, they may separate to form two or more different types of crystals, creating a heterogeneous microstructure of different phases, some with more of one constituent than the other.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, in other alloys, the insoluble elements may not separate until after crystallization occurs.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] If cooled very quickly, they first crystallize as a homogeneous phase, but they are supersaturated with the secondary constituents.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] As time passes, the atoms of these supersaturated alloys can separate from the crystal lattice, becoming more stable, and forming a second phase that serves to reinforce the crystals internally.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Some alloys, such as electrum—an alloy of silver and gold—occur naturally.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Meteorites are sometimes made of naturally occurring alloys of iron and nickel, but are not native to the Earth.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] One of the first alloys made by humans was bronze, which is a mixture of the metals tin and copper.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Bronze was an extremely useful alloy to the ancients, because it is much stronger and harder than either of its components.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, in ancient times, it could only be created as an accidental byproduct from the heating of iron ore in fires (smelting) during the manufacture of iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Other ancient alloys include pewter, brass, and pig iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In the modern age, steel can be created in many forms.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Carbon steel can be made by varying only the carbon content, producing soft alloys like mild steel or hard alloys like spring steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Alloy steels can be made by adding other elements, such as chromium, molybdenum, vanadium, or nickel, resulting in alloys such as high-speed steel or tool steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Small amounts of manganese are usually alloyed with most modern steels because of its ability to remove unwanted impurities, like phosphorus, sulfur, and oxygen, which can have detrimental effects on the alloy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, most alloys were not created until the 1900s, such as various aluminium, titanium, nickel, and magnesium alloys.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Some modern superalloys, such as incoloy, inconel, and hastelloy, may consist of a multitude of different elements.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] An alloy is technically an impure metal, but when referring to alloys, the term *impurities* usually denotes undesirable elements.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Such impurities are introduced from the base metals and alloying elements, but are removed during processing.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For instance, sulfur is a common impurity in steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Sulfur combines readily with iron to form iron sulfide, which is very brittle, creating weak spots in the steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Lithium, sodium and calcium are common impurities in aluminium alloys, which can have adverse effects on the structural integrity of castings.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Conversely, otherwise pure-metals that contain unwanted impurities are often called "impure metals" and are not usually referred to as alloys.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Impure metals such as cast iron or wrought iron are less controlled, but are often considered useful.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Oxygen, present in the air, readily combines with most metals to form metal oxides, especially at higher temperatures encountered during alloying.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Depending on the alloy, this can eventually result in a failure of the component being produced.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Great care is often taken during the alloying process to remove excess impurities, using fluxes, chemical additives, or other methods of extractive metallurgy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Alloying a metal is done by combining it with one or more other elements.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The most common and oldest alloying process is performed by heating the base metal beyond its melting point and then dissolving the solutes into the molten liquid, which may be possible even if the melting point of the solute is far greater than that of the base.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For example, in its liquid state, titanium is a very strong solvent capable of dissolving most metals and elements.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In addition, it readily absorbs gases like oxygen and burns in the presence of nitrogen.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This increases the chance of contamination from any contacting surface, and so must be melted in vacuum induction-heating and special, water-cooled, copper crucibles.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Carbon has a very high melting-point and only does so under high atmospheric pressure, so it was impossible for ancient civilizations to combine with iron as a liquid solute.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] It may also be done with one, more, or all of the constituents in the solid state, such as found in ancient methods of pattern welding (solid-solid), shear steel (solid-solid), or crucible steel production (solid-liquid), mixing the elements via solid-state diffusion.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] By adding another element to a metal, differences in the size of the atoms create internal stresses in the lattice of the metallic crystals; stresses that often enhance its properties.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For example, the combination of carbon with wrought iron produces steel, which is stronger than iron, its primary element.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The electrical and thermal conductivity of alloys is usually lower than that of the pure metals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The physical properties, such as density, reactivity, Young's modulus of an alloy may not differ greatly from those of its base element, but engineering properties such as tensile strength, ductility, and shear strength may be substantially different from those of the constituent materials.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This is sometimes a result of the sizes of the atoms in the alloy, because larger atoms exert a compressive force on neighboring atoms, and smaller atoms exert a tensile force on their neighbors, helping the alloy resist deformation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Sometimes alloys may exhibit marked differences in behavior even when small amounts of one element are present.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For example, impurities in semiconducting ferromagnetic alloys lead to different properties, as first predicted by White, Hogan, Suhl, Tian Abrie and Nakamura.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Unlike pure metals, most alloys do not have a single melting point, but a melting range during which the material is a mixture of solid and liquid phases (a slush).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The temperature at which melting begins is called the solidus, and the temperature when melting is just complete is called the liquidus.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For many alloys there is a particular alloy proportion (in some cases more than one), called either a eutectic mixture or a peritectic composition, which gives the alloy a unique and low melting point, and no liquid/solid slush transition.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Alloying elements are added to a base metal, to induce hardness, toughness, ductility, or other desired properties.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Many metals and alloys can be work hardened by creating defects in their crystal structure.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These defects are created during plastic deformation by hammering, bending, extruding, et cetera, and are permanent unless the metal is recrystallized.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Otherwise, some alloys can also have their properties altered by heat treatment.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Nearly all metals can be softened by annealing, which recrystallizes the alloy and repairs the defects, but not as many can be hardened by controlled heating and cooling.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Many alloys of aluminium, copper, magnesium, titanium, and nickel can be strengthened to some degree by some method of heat treatment, but few respond to this to the same degree as does steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The base metal iron of the iron-carbon alloy known as steel, undergoes a change in the arrangement (allotropy) of the atoms of its crystal matrix at a certain temperature (usually 820 °C (1,500 °F) or more, depending on carbon content).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This allows the smaller carbon atoms to enter the interstices of the iron crystal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] When this diffusion happens, the carbon atoms are said to be in *solution* in the iron, forming a particular single, homogeneous, crystalline phase called austenite.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] If the steel is cooled slowly, the carbon can diffuse out of the iron and it will gradually revert to its low temperature allotrope.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] During slow cooling, the carbon atoms will no longer be as soluble with the iron, and will be forced to precipitate out of solution, nucleating into a more concentrated form of iron carbide (Fe3C) in the spaces between the pure iron crystals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The steel then becomes heterogeneous, as it is formed of two phases, the iron-carbon phase called cementite (or carbide), and pure iron ferrite.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Such a heat treatment produces a steel that is rather soft.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] If the steel is cooled quickly, however, the carbon atoms will not have time to diffuse and precipitate out as carbide, but will be trapped within the iron crystals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] When rapidly cooled, a diffusionless (martensite) transformation occurs, in which the carbon atoms become trapped in solution.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This causes the iron crystals to deform as the crystal structure tries to change to its low temperature state, leaving those crystals very hard but much less ductile (more brittle).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] While the high strength of steel results when diffusion and precipitation is prevented (forming martensite), most heat-treatable alloys are precipitation hardening alloys, that depend on the diffusion of alloying elements to achieve their strength.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] When heated to form a solution and then cooled quickly, these alloys become much softer than normal, during the diffusionless transformation, but then harden as they age.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The solutes in these alloys will precipitate over time, forming intermetallic phases, which are difficult to discern from the base metal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Unlike steel, in which the solid solution separates into different crystal phases (carbide and ferrite), precipitation hardening alloys form different phases within the same crystal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These intermetallic alloys appear homogeneous in crystal structure, but tend to behave heterogeneously, becoming hard and somewhat brittle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In 1906, precipitation hardening alloys were discovered by Alfred Wilm.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Precipitation hardening alloys, such as certain alloys of aluminium, titanium, and copper, are heat-treatable alloys that soften when quenched (cooled quickly), and then harden over time.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Wilm had been searching for a way to harden aluminium alloys for use in machine-gun cartridge cases.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Knowing that aluminium-copper alloys were heat-treatable to some degree, Wilm tried quenching a ternary alloy of aluminium, copper, and the addition of magnesium, but was initially disappointed with the results.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, when Wilm retested it the next day he discovered that the alloy increased in hardness when left to age at room temperature, and far exceeded his expectations.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Although an explanation for the phenomenon was not provided until 1919, duralumin was one of the first "age hardening" alloys used, becoming the primary building material for the first Zeppelins, and was soon followed by many others.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Because they often exhibit a combination of high strength and low weight, these alloys became widely used in many forms of industry, including the construction of modern aircraft.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] When a molten metal is mixed with another substance, there are two mechanisms that can cause an alloy to form, called *atom exchange* and the *interstitial mechanism*.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The relative size of each element in the mix plays a primary role in determining which mechanism will occur.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] When the atoms are relatively similar in size, the atom exchange method usually happens, where some of the atoms composing the metallic crystals are substituted with atoms of the other constituent.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This is called a *substitutional alloy*.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Examples of substitutional alloys include bronze and brass, in which some of the copper atoms are substituted with either tin or zinc atoms respectively.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In the case of the interstitial mechanism, one atom is usually much smaller than the other and can not successfully substitute for the other type of atom in the crystals of the base metal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Instead, the smaller atoms become trapped in the interstitial sites between the atoms of the crystal matrix.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This is referred to as an *interstitial alloy*.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Steel is an example of an interstitial alloy, because the very small carbon atoms fit into interstices of the iron matrix.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Stainless steel is an example of a combination of interstitial and substitutional alloys, because the carbon atoms fit into the interstices, but some of the iron atoms are substituted by nickel and chromium atoms.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The use of alloys by humans started with the use of meteoric iron, a naturally occurring alloy of nickel and iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] It is the main constituent of iron meteorites.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] As no metallurgic processes were used to separate iron from nickel, the alloy was used as it was.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Meteoric iron could be forged from a red heat to make objects such as tools, weapons, and nails.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In many cultures it was shaped by cold hammering into knives and arrowheads.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Meteoric iron was very rare and valuable, and difficult for ancient people to work.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Iron is usually found as iron ore on Earth, except for one deposit of native iron in Greenland, which was used by the Inuit.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Native copper, however, was found worldwide, along with silver, gold, and platinum, which were also used to make tools, jewelry, and other objects since Neolithic times.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Copper was the hardest of these metals, and the most widely distributed.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] It became one of the most important metals to the ancients.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Starting around 10,000 years ago in the highlands of Anatolia (Turkey), humans learned to smelt metals such as copper and tin from ore.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Early bronze alloys used copper and arsenic, but the latter can be toxic to the metal-workers.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Around 2500 BC, people began alloying tin and copper to form bronze, which was much harder than its ingredients.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, tin was rare, being found mostly in Great Britain.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In the Middle East, people began alloying copper with zinc to form brass.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Ancient civilizations took into account the mixture and the various properties it produced, such as hardness, toughness and melting point, under various conditions of temperature and work hardening, developing much of the information contained in modern alloy phase diagrams.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For example, arrowheads from the Chinese Qin dynasty (around 200 BC) were often constructed with a hard bronze-head, but a softer bronze-tang, combining the alloys to prevent both dulling and breaking during use.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Mercury has been smelted from cinnabar for thousands of years.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Mercury dissolves many metals, such as gold, silver, and tin, to form amalgams (an alloy in a soft paste or liquid form at ambient temperature).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Amalgams have been used since 200 BC in China for gilding objects such as armor and mirrors with precious metals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The ancient Romans often used mercury-tin amalgams for gilding their armor.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The amalgam was applied as a paste and then heated until the mercury vaporized, leaving the gold, silver, or tin behind.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Mercury was often used in mining, to extract precious metals like gold and silver from their ores.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Many ancient civilizations alloyed metals for purely aesthetic purposes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In ancient Egypt and Mycenae, gold was often alloyed with copper to produce red-gold, or iron to produce a bright burgundy-gold.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Gold was often found alloyed with silver or other metals to produce various types of colored gold.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These metals were also used to strengthen each other, for more practical purposes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Copper was often added to silver to make sterling silver, increasing its strength for use in dishes, silverware, and other practical items.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Quite often, precious metals were alloyed with less valuable substances as a means to deceive buyers.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Around 250 BC, Archimedes was commissioned by the King of Syracuse to find a way to check the purity of the gold in a crown, leading to the famous bath-house shouting of "Eureka!" upon the discovery of Archimedes' principle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The term pewter covers a variety of alloys consisting primarily of tin.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] As a pure metal, tin is much too soft to use for most practical purposes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, during the Bronze Age, tin was a rare metal in many parts of Europe and the Mediterranean, so it was often valued higher than gold.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] To make jewellery, cutlery, or other objects from tin, workers usually alloyed it with other metals to increase strength and hardness.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These metals were typically lead, antimony, bismuth or copper.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These solutes were sometimes added individually in varying amounts, or added together, making a wide variety of objects, ranging from practical items such as dishes, surgical tools, candlesticks or funnels, to decorative items like ear rings and hair clips.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The earliest examples of pewter come from ancient Egypt, around 1450 BC.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The use of pewter was widespread across Europe, from France to Norway and Britain (where most of the ancient tin was mined) to the Near East.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The alloy was also used in China and the Far East, arriving in Japan around 800 AD, where it was used for making objects like ceremonial vessels, tea canisters, or chalices used in shinto shrines.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The first known smelting of iron began in Anatolia, around 1800 BC.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Called the bloomery process, it produced very soft but ductile wrought iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] By 800 BC, iron-making technology had spread to Europe, arriving in Japan around 700 AD.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Pig iron, a very hard but brittle alloy of iron and carbon, was being produced in China as early as 1200 BC, but did not arrive in Europe until the Middle Ages.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Pig iron has a lower melting point than iron, and was used for making cast iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, these metals found little practical use until the introduction of crucible steel around 300 BC.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These steels were of poor quality, and the introduction of pattern welding, around the 1st century AD, sought to balance the extreme properties of the alloys by laminating them, to create a tougher metal.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Around 700 AD, the Japanese began folding bloomery-steel and cast iron in alternating layers to increase the strength of their swords, using clay fluxes to remove slag and impurities.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This method of Japanese swordsmithing produced one of the purest steel-alloys of the ancient world.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] While the use of iron started to become more widespread around 1200 BC, mainly because of interruptions in the trade routes for tin, the metal was much softer than bronze.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, very small amounts of steel, (an alloy of iron and around 1% carbon), was always a byproduct of the bloomery process.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The ability to modify the hardness of steel by heat treatment had been known since 1100 BC, and the rare material was valued for the manufacture of tools and weapons.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Because the ancients could not produce temperatures high enough to melt iron fully, the production of steel in decent quantities did not occur until the introduction of blister steel during the Middle Ages.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] This method introduced carbon by heating wrought iron in charcoal for long periods of time, but the absorption of carbon in this manner is extremely slow thus the penetration was not very deep, so the alloy was not homogeneous.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In 1740, Benjamin Huntsman began melting blister steel in a crucible to even out the carbon content, creating the first process for the mass production of tool steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Huntsman's process was used for manufacturing tool steel until the early 1900s.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The introduction of the blast furnace to Europe in the Middle Ages meant that people could produce pig iron in much higher volumes than wrought iron.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Because pig iron could be melted, people began to develop processes to reduce carbon in liquid pig iron to create steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Puddling had been used in China since the first century, and was introduced in Europe during the 1700s, where molten pig iron was stirred while exposed to the air, to remove the carbon by oxidation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In 1858, Henry Bessemer developed a process of steel-making by blowing hot air through liquid pig iron to reduce the carbon content.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The Bessemer process led to the first large scale manufacture of steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Steel is an alloy of iron and carbon, but the term *alloy steel* usually only refers to steels that contain other elements— like vanadium, molybdenum, or cobalt—in amounts sufficient to alter the properties of the base steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Since ancient times, when steel was used primarily for tools and weapons, the methods of producing and working the metal were often closely guarded secrets.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Even long after the Age of Enlightenment, the steel industry was very competitive and manufacturers went through great lengths to keep their processes confidential, resisting any attempts to scientifically analyze the material for fear it would reveal their methods.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] For example, the people of Sheffield, a center of steel production in England, were known to routinely bar visitors and tourists from entering town to deter industrial espionage.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Thus, almost no metallurgical information existed about steel until 1860.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Afterward, many people began experimenting with various alloys of steel without much success.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, in 1882, Robert Hadfield, being a pioneer in steel metallurgy, took an interest and produced a steel alloy containing around 12% manganese.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Called mangalloy, it exhibited extreme hardness and toughness, becoming the first commercially viable alloy-steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Afterward, he created silicon steel, launching the search for other possible alloys of steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Robert Forester Mushet found that by adding tungsten to steel it could produce a very hard edge that would resist losing its hardness at high temperatures.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Mushet's special steel" (RMS) became the first high-speed steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Mushet's steel was quickly replaced by tungsten carbide steel, developed by Taylor and White in 1900, in which they doubled the tungsten content and added small amounts of chromium and vanadium, producing a superior steel for use in lathes and machining tools.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In 1903, the Wright brothers used a chromium-nickel steel to make the crankshaft for their airplane engine, while in 1908 Henry Ford began using vanadium steels for parts like crankshafts and valves in his Model T Ford, due to their higher strength and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In 1912, the Krupp Ironworks in Germany developed a rust-resistant steel by adding 21% chromium and 7% nickel, producing the first stainless steel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] A typical example of a modern alloy is 304 grade stainless steel which is commonly used for kitchen utensils, pans, knives and forks.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Sometime also known as 18/8, it as an alloy consisting broadly of 74% iron, 18% chromium and 8% nickel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The chromium and nickel alloying elements add strength and hardness to the majority iron element, but their main function is to make it resistant to rust/corrosion.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Due to their high reactivity, most metals were not discovered until the 19th century.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] A method for extracting aluminium from bauxite was proposed by Humphry Davy in 1807, using an electric arc.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Although his attempts were unsuccessful, by 1855 the first sales of pure aluminium reached the market.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, as extractive metallurgy was still in its infancy, most aluminium extraction-processes produced unintended alloys contaminated with other elements found in the ore; the most abundant of which was copper.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These aluminium-copper alloys (at the time termed "aluminium bronze") preceded pure aluminium, offering greater strength and hardness over the soft, pure metal, and to a slight degree were found to be heat treatable.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] However, due to their softness and limited hardenability these alloys found little practical use, and were more of a novelty, until the Wright brothers used an aluminium alloy to construct the first airplane engine in 1903.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] During the time between 1865 and 1910, processes for extracting many other metals were discovered, such as chromium, vanadium, tungsten, iridium, cobalt, and molybdenum, and various alloys were developed.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] Prior to 1910, research mainly consisted of private individuals tinkering in their own laboratories.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] The Doehler Die Casting Co. of Toledo, Ohio were known for the production of *Brastil*, a high tensile corrosion resistant bronze alloy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] As a part of industrial procurement for the production of precision alloys, intermediate good 'master alloy' ingots or powder are produced with a consistent mixture of desired metal content.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] These master alloys can then be combined to produce the final desired alloy for production.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/alloy] In the aluminium alloy industry, master alloy is commonly introduced to aluminium to adjust the metal grain of the final alloy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] An **axe** (/æks/; sometimes spelled **ax** in American English; see spelling differences) is an implement that has been used for thousands of years to shape, split, and cut wood, to harvest timber, and as a weapon.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The axe has many forms and specialised uses but generally consists of a head with a sharpened blade (also called a "bit") attached to a handle (also called "haft" or "helve").
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Before the modern axe, the stone-age hand axe without a handle was used from 1.5 million years BP.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Hafted axes (those with a handle) date from at least 46,000 years BP by Northern Indigenous Australians.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The earliest examples of handled axes have heads of stone with some form of wooden handle attached (hafted) in a method to suit the available materials and use.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Axes made of copper, bronze, iron and steel appeared as these technologies developed.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The axe is an example of a simple machine, as it is a type of wedge, or dual inclined plane.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] This reduces the effort needed by the wood chopper.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] It cuts and splits the wood into two parts by the pressure concentration at the blade and then the movement of the head in behind the initial cut.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The handle of the axe also acts as a lever allowing the user to increase the force at the cutting edge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Generally, the blades of 'cutting axes', which are used for felling, limbing, and bucking, have a shallow (acute) wedge angle, whereas 'splitting axes' have a deeper (more obtuse) angle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Most axes are double bevelled (i.e. symmetrical about the axis of the blade), but some specialist broadaxes have a single bevel blade.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Most modern axes have steel heads and wooden handles, although plastic or fibreglass handles are also common.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Modern axes are specialised by use, size and form.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Hafted axes with short handles designed for use with one hand are often called "hand axes", but the term "hand axe" can also refer to an axe without a handle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Hatchets tend to be short-, small-hafted axes often with a hammer on the back side (the poll, or butt).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Relatively easy to make and use, the axe has frequently been used in combat, and is one of humanity's oldest weapons.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Axes are also linchpins to the competitive sport of wood-chopping.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Hand axes, of stone, and used without handles (hafts) were the first axes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] They had knapped (chipped) cutting edges of flint or other stone.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Early examples of hand axes date back to 1.6 mya in the later Oldowan, in Southern Ethiopia around 1.4 mya, and in 1.2 mya deposits in Olduvai Gorge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Hafted axes are first known from the Mesolithic period (c.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Few wooden hafts have been found from this period, but it seems that the axe was normally hafted by wedging.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Birch-tar and rawhide lashings were used to fix the blade.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The distribution of stone axes is an important indication of prehistoric trade.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Thin sectioning is used to determine the provenance of the stone blades.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Stone axes are still produced and in use today in parts of Papua, Indonesia.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The Mount Hagen area of Papua New Guinea was an important production centre.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] From the late Neolithic/Chalcolithic onwards, axes were made of copper or copper mixed with arsenic.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] These axes were flat and hafted much like their stone predecessors.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Axes continued to be made in this manner with the introduction of bronze metallurgy.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Eventually the hafting method changed and the flat axe developed into the "flanged axe", then palstaves, and later winged and socketed axes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] At least since the late Neolithic, elaborate axes (battle-axes, T-axes, etc.) had a religious significance and probably indicated the exalted status of their owner.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Certain types almost never show traces of wear; deposits of unshafted axe blades from the middle Neolithic (such as at the Somerset Levels in Britain) may have been gifts to the deities.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] In Minoan Crete, the double axe (labrys) had a special significance, used by priestesses in religious ceremonies.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] In 1998, a labrys, complete with an elaborately embellished haft, was found at Cham-Eslen, Canton of Zug, Switzerland.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The haft was 120 cm (47 in) long and wrapped in ornamented birch-bark.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The axe blade is 17.4 cm (6.9 in) long and made of antigorite, mined in the Gotthard-area.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The haft goes through a biconical drilled hole and is fastened by wedges of antler and by birch-tar.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] It belongs to the early Cortaillod culture.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The coat of arms of Norway features a lion rampant carrying an axe which represents King Olaf II of Norway, who was honoured as the Eternal King of Norway.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] In folklore, stone axes were sometimes believed to be thunderbolts and were used to guard buildings against lightning, as it was believed (mythically) that lightning never struck the same place twice.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] This has caused some skewing of axe distributions.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Steel axes were important in superstition as well.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] A thrown axe could keep off a hailstorm, sometimes an axe was placed in the crops, with the cutting edge to the skies to protect the harvest against bad weather.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] An upright axe buried under the sill of a house would keep off witches, while an axe under the bed would assure male offspring.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Basques, Australians and New Zealanders have developed variants of rural sports that perpetuate the traditions of log cutting with axe.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The Basque variants, splitting horizontally or vertically disposed logs, are generically called *aizkolaritza* (from *aizkora*: axe).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] In Yorùbá mythology, the oshe (double-headed axe) symbolises Shango, Orisha (god) of thunder and lightning.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] It is said to represent swift and balanced justice.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Shango altars often contain a carved figure of a woman holding a gift to the god with a double-bladed axe sticking up from her head.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The Hurrian and Hittite weather god Teshub is depicted on a bas-relief at Ivriz wielding a thunderbolt and an axe.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The Arkalochori Axe is a bronze Minoan axe from the second millennium BC thought to be used for religious purposes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Inscriptions on this axe have been compared with other ancient writing systems.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] In Mark Masonry, the axe is a symbol of punishment meant to remind Mark Master Masons to be truthful and avoid deceit.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Hammer axes (or axe-hammers) typically feature an extended poll, opposite the blade, shaped and sometimes hardened for use as a hammer.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] The name axe-hammer is often applied to a characteristic shape of perforated stone axe used in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Iron axe-hammers are found in Roman military contexts, e.g.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/axe] Cramond, Edinburgh, and South Shields, Tyne and Wear.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] A **bandsaw** (also written **band saw**) is a power saw with a long, sharp blade with two ends welded together to form an oval band.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The banded blade of toothed metal is stretched between two or more wheels to cut material.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] They are used principally in woodworking, metalworking, and lumber milling, but may cut a variety of materials.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Advantages include uniform cutting action as a result of an evenly distributed tooth load, and the ability to cut irregular or curved shapes like a jigsaw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The minimum radius of a curve is determined by the width of the band and its kerf.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Most bandsaws have two wheels rotating in the same plane, one of which is powered, although some may have three or four to distribute the load.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The blade itself can come in a variety of sizes and tooth pitches (teeth per inch, or TPI), which enables the machine to be highly versatile and able to cut a wide variety of materials including wood, metal and plastic.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] A band saw is recommended for use in cutting metal as it produces much less toxic fumes and particulates when compared with an angle grinder or reciprocating saw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Almost all bandsaws today are powered by an electric motor.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The idea of the bandsaw dates back to at least 1809, when William Newberry received a British patent for the idea, but bandsaws remained impractical largely because of the inability to produce accurate and durable blades using the technology of the day.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Constant flexing of the blade over the wheels caused either the material or the joint welding it into a loop to fail.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Nearly 40 years passed before Frenchwoman Anne Paulin Crepin devised a welding technique overcoming this hurdle.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] She applied for a patent in 1846, and soon afterward sold the right to employ it to manufacturer A.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Combining this method with new steel alloys and advanced tempering techniques allowed Perin to create the first modern bandsaw blade.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The first American bandsaw patent was granted to Benjamin Barker of Ellsworth, Maine, in January 1836.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The first factory produced and commercially available bandsaw in the U.S. was by a design of Paul Prybil.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Power hacksaws (with reciprocating blades) were once common in the metalworking industries, but bandsaws and cold saws have mostly displaced them.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Many workshops in residential garages or basements and in light industry contain small or medium-sized bandsaws that can cut wood, metal, or plastic.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Often a general-purpose blade is left in place, although blades optimized for wood or metal can be switched out when volume of use warrants.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Most residential and commercial bandsaws are of the vertical type mounted on a bench or a cabinet stand.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Portable power tool versions, including cordless models, are also common in recent decades, allowing building contractors to bring them along on the truck to the jobsite.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Saws for cutting meat are typically of all stainless steel construction with easy to clean features.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The blades either have fine teeth with heat treated tips, or have plain or scalloped knife edges.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Bandsaws dedicated to industrial metal-cutting use, such as for structural steel in fabrication shops and for bar stock in machine shops, are available in vertical and horizontal designs.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Typical band speeds range from 40 ft/min (0.20 m/s) to 5,000 ft/min (25 m/s), although specialized bandsaws are built for friction cutting of hard metals and run band speeds of 15,000 ft/min (76 m/s).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Metal-cutting bandsaws are usually equipped with brushes or brushwheels to prevent chips from becoming stuck in between the blade's teeth.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Systems which cool the blade with cutting fluid are also common equipment on metal-cutting bandsaws.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The coolant washes away swarf and keeps the blade cool and lubricated.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Horizontal bandsaws hold the workpiece stationary while the blade swings down through the cut.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This configuration is used to cut long materials such as pipe or bar stock to length.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Thus it is an important part of the facilities in most machine shops.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The horizontal design is not useful for cutting curves or complicated shapes.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Small horizontal bandsaws typically employ a gravity feed alone, retarded to an adjustable degree by a coil spring; on industrial models, the rate of descent is usually controlled by a hydraulic cylinder that bleeds through an adjustable valve.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] When the saw is set up for a cut, the operator raises the saw, positions the material to be cut underneath the blade, and then turns on the saw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The blade slowly descends into the material, cutting it as the band blade moves.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] When the cut is complete, a switch is tripped and the saw automatically turns off.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] More sophisticated versions of this type of saw are partially or entirely automated (via PLC or CNC) for high-volume cutting of machining blanks.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Such machines provide a stream of cutting fluid recirculated from a sump, in the same manner that a CNC machining center does.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] A vertical bandsaw, also called a contour saw, keeps the blade's path stationary while the workpiece is moved across it.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This type of saw can be used to cut out complex shapes and angles.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The part may be fed into the blade manually or with a power assist mechanism.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This type of metal-cutting bandsaw is often equipped with a built-in blade welder.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This not only allows the operator to repair broken blades or fabricate new blades quickly, but also allows for the blade to be purposely cut, routed through the center of a part, and re-welded in order to make interior cuts.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] These saws are often fitted with a built-in air blower to cool the blade and to blow chips away from the cut area giving the operator a clear view of the work.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This type of saw is also built in a woodworking version.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The woodworking type is generally of much lighter construction and does not incorporate a power feed mechanism, coolant, or welder.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Advancements have also been made in the bandsaw blades used to cut metals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Bimetal blades with high speed steel teeth, including cobalt grades, are now the norm.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The development of new tooth geometries and tooth pitches has produced increased production rates and greater blade life.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] New materials and processes such as M51 steel and the cryogenic treatment of blades have produced results that were thought impossible just a few years ago.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] New machines have been developed to automate the welding process of bandsaw blades as well.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Timber mills use very large bandsaws for ripping lumber; they are preferred over circular saws for ripping because they can accommodate large-diameter timber and because of their smaller kerf (cut size), resulting in less waste.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] There are also small portable sawmills consisting of a somewhat smaller bandsaw mounted on a guiding table, which are called bandsaw mills (band saw mills, band sawmills).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Like chain saw mills (a chainsaw on a guiding table), they can be used inexpensively by one or two people out in the field.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] These tools may be used by off-gridders and those doing small scale lumber processing in remote areas.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Today, even these mills may be powered by electricity.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] In a full-size sawmill, the blades are mounted on wheels with a diameter large enough not to cause metal fatigue due to flexing when the blade repeatedly changes from a circular to a straight profile.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] It is stretched very tight (with fatigue strength of the saw metal being the limiting factor).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Bandsaws of this size need to have a deformation worked into them that counteracts the forces and heating of operation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] They also need to be removed and serviced at regular intervals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Sawfilers or sawdoctors are the craftsmen responsible for this work.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The shape of the tooth gullet is highly optimized and designed by the sawyer and sawfiler.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] It varies according to the mill, as well as the type and condition of the wood.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Frozen logs often require a "frost notch" ground into the gullet to break the chips.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The shape of the tooth gullet is created when the blade is manufactured and its shape is automatically maintained with each sharpening.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The sawfiler will need to maintain the grinding wheel's profile with periodic dressing of the wheel.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Proper tracking of the blade is crucial to accurate cutting and considerably reduces blade breakage.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The first step to ensuring good tracking is to check that the two bandwheels or flywheels are co-planar.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This can be done by placing a straightedge across the front of the wheels and adjusting until each wheel touches on both its top and bottom.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Rotate the wheels with the blade in position and properly tensioned and check that the tracking is correct.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Now install the blade guide rollers and leave a gap of about 1mm between the back of the blade and the guide flange.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] The teeth of blades that have become narrow through repeated sharpening will foul the front edge of the guide rollers due to their kerf set and force the blade out of alignment.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] This can be remedied by cutting of a small step on the rollers' front edges to accommodate the protruding teeth.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Ideally the rollers should be crowned, (see belt and pulley systems) a configuration that assists in the proper tracking of bands and belts, at the same time allowing clearance for the set of the teeth.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Head saws are large bandsaws that make the initial cuts in a log.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] They generally have a 2 to 3 in (51 to 76 mm) tooth space on the cutting edge and *sliver teeth* on the back.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Sliver teeth are non-cutting teeth designed to wipe slivers out of the way when the blade needs to back out of a cut.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] A resaw is a large bandsaw optimized for cutting timber along the grain to reduce larger sections into smaller sections or veneers.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Resawing veneers requires a wide blade—commonly 2 to 3 in (51 to 76 mm)—with a small kerf to minimize waste.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Resaw blades of up to 1 in (25 mm) may be fitted to a standard bandsaw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Double cut saws have cutting teeth on both sides.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] They are generally very large, similar in size to a head saw.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Automatic bandsaws feature preset feed rate, return, fall, part feeding, and part clamping.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] These are used in production environments where having a machine operator per saw is not practical.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] One operator can feed and unload many automatic saws.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] Some automatic saws rely on numerical control to not only cut faster, but to be more precise and perform more complex miter cuts.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/bandsaw] At least two teeth must be in contact with the workpiece at all times to avoid stripping off the teeth.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] In the context of machining, a **cutting tool** or **cutter** is typically a hardened metal tool that is used to cut, shape, and remove material from a workpiece by means of machining tools as well as abrasive tools by way of shear deformation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The majority of these tools are designed for metals, but are also used on hard rubber, synthetic resins, slate, marble, and other materials.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] There are several different types of single-edge cutting tools that are made from a variety of hardened metal alloys that are ground to a specific shape in order to perform a specific part of the turning process resulting in a finished machined part.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Single-edge cutting tools are used mainly in the turning operations performed by a lathe in which they vary in size as well as alloy composition depending on the size and the type of material being turned.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] These cutting tools are held stationary by what is known as a *tool post*.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Single-edge cutting tools are also the means of cutting material performed by shaping machines and planing machines, which remove material by means of one cutting edge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Milling tools are often multipoint tools, that, while sometimes near identical in appearance, are distinguished from drill bits in its application, geometry, and manufacture.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] While a drill bit can only cut in the axial direction (drilling), most milling bits can cut in the radial direction.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Near all drill bits have two cutting edges that are ground into equally tapered angles that cut through the material by applying downward rotational force.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Endmills or milling bits, also cut material by rotational force.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] These tools do more than put holes in a workpiece, they cut by horizontal shear deformation in which the workpiece is brought into the tool as it's rotating.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The tool path is determined by the movement of the table that is holding the workpiece in place.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] This table is designed to accept a variety of vises and clamping tools so that the affixed workpiece can move into the cutter at various angles and directions.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] There are multiple different types of endmills that perform a different milling actions.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Grinding stones are tools that contain several different cutting edges which encompasses the entirety of the stone.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Unlike metallic cutting tools, these grinding stones never go dull.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] In fact the formation of cutting edges of metallic cutting tools are achieved by the use of grinding wheels and other hard abrasives.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] There are several different types of grinding stone wheels that are used to grind several different types of metals.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Although these stones are not metal, they need to be harder than the metal that they grind.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] In contrast to the grinding stone, if the hardness of the metal exceeds that of the stone, the metal will cut the stone.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Each grain of abrasive functions as a microscopic single-point cutting edge (although of high negative rake angle), and shears a tiny chip.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Cutting tool materials must be harder than the material which is to be cut, and the tool must be able to withstand the heat and force generated in the metal-cutting process.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Also, the tool must have a specific geometry, with clearance angles designed so that the cutting edge can contact the workpiece without the rest of the tool dragging on the workpiece surface.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The angle of the cutting face is also important, as is the flute width, number of flutes or teeth, and margin size.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] In order to have a long working life, all of the above must be optimized, plus the speeds and feeds at which the tool is run.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Linear cutting tools include tool bits (single-point cutting tools) and broaches.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Rotary cutting tools include drill bits, countersinks and counterbores, taps and dies, reamers, and cold saw blades.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Other cutting tools, such as bandsaw blades, hacksaw blades, and fly cutters, combine aspects of linear and rotary motion.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The majority of these types of cutting tools are often made from HSS (High-Speed-Steel).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Cutting tools are often designed with inserts or replaceable tips (tipped tools).
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] In these, the cutting edge consists of a separate piece of material, either brazed, welded or clamped on to the tool body.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Common materials for tips include cemented carbide, polycrystalline diamond, and cubic boron nitride.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Tools using inserts include milling cutters (endmills, fly cutters), tool bits, and saw blades.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The detailed instructions of how to combine the tool assembly out of basic holder, tool and insert can be stored in a tool management solution.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The cutting edge of a cutting tool is a very important for the performance of the cutting process.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] The measurement of the cutting edge is performed using a tactile instrument or an instrument using focus variation.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] One of the most important cutting edge parameters is the K factor.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] It specifies the form of the cutting edge.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] If the value is smaller than 1 the form is called a waterfall.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] If the value is larger than 1 it is called a trumpet.
[src:cutting-tool-machining/cutting-tool-machining] Depending on the material being cut, feed rate and other factors, a cutting tool with the optimum K factor should be used.
